@kirklund Thanks , will add the test
As you can see from your test:
/Users/klund/dev/gemfire_CLEAN/open/geode-assembly/build/install/apache-geode/lib/geode-core-1.4.0-SNAPSHOT.jar
/Users/klund/dev/gemfire_CLEAN/open/tmp/geode-core-1.4.0-SNAPSHOT.jar

The first sting is class path for geode-core-1.4.0-SNAPSHOT.jar is from GEODE_HOME/lib, so the jar in the classpath you provided as argument will not be taken ( as it comes second) 

But if you try to add /Users/klund/dev/gemfire_CLEAN/open/tmpgemfire-core-8.2.0.0-SNAPSHOT.jar as gfsh classpath argument , you will see it first 


With my fix, the order will be reversed and PF taken for current version of geode-core jar  , you will see: 

/Users/klund/dev/gemfire_CLEAN/open/tmp/geode-core-1.4.0-SNAPSHOT.jar
/Users/klund/dev/gemfire_CLEAN/open/geode-assembly/build/install/apache-geode/lib/geode-core-1.4.0-SNAPSHOT.jar

That is because the function uses GEODE_JAR_PATHNAME( that is GEODE_HOME/lib) as default, and only replaces it  if user classpath has the string that was hardcoded before my fix  

     String classpath = getSystemClasspath();
      String gemfireJarPath = GEODE_JAR_PATHNAME;
      for (String classpathElement : classpath.split(File.pathSeparator)) {
 -      if (classpathElement.endsWith("gemfire-core-8.2.0.0-SNAPSHOT.jar")) {
 +      if (classpathElement.endsWith("geode-core-" + GemFireVersion.getGemFireVersion() + ".jar")) {
          gemfireJarPath = classpathElement;
          break;

@kirklund But isn't current situation inconsistent , and this fix fixes it?

If  add location of  any other  geode jar  to classpath as argument , it will always come first  , before GEODE_HOME. Only specifically geode-core jar , we can't override, because of old hard-coded value in this function.

I can add comment to explain what was the reasoning
